Madison Avenue, at the N. W. corner of East 100th Street, showing rural conditions prevalent near Carnegie Hill. The Avenue is paved and street car tracks are in the center thereof.

The data on the reverse side of this print gives the location as Amsterdam Avenue and 100th Street on Sept. 21, 1894. It appeared in the N. Y. Sun on February 11, 1929 as No. 122 in the series titled "Old New York in Pictures" and identified as Amsterdam Avenue.
Mr. Hoffman of the New York Historical Society identifies this as the corrected location, basing his conclusions from a view taken from atop the Ruppert house at 5th Ave. and 93rd Street. Both of these views are in their collection.

About 1894

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Madison Avenue, at the N.W. corner of 100th Street. The view shows a Squatters Settlement, consisting of 1 and 2-story frame shacks. Trees in the background are on the Fifth Avenue side of Central Park. Note the paved condition of the Avenue and the street car tracks thereupon. This photo appeared in the New York Sun of February 11, 1929 as No. 122 in the series titled "Old N.Y. in Pictures" and was identified as Amsterdam Avenue. The corrected location is attributable to Mr. Hoffman of the New York Historical Society who bases his identification on a view taken from atop the Ruppert house at Fifth Avenue and 97th Street. This organization has both views.

About 1894

H. N. Tiemann Company
Brown Brothers

Madison Avenue, at the N. W. corner of E. 100th St. showing rural conditions prevalent in the locality known as "Carnegie Hill".
Data on the reverse side of this print reads: Carnegie Hill--5th Ave. and 90th Street. Mr. Hoffman of the N.Y.H.S. identifies this location as corrected above, basing his conclusions from a view taken from atop the Ruppert house at 5th Avenue and 93rd Street.

Madison Avenue, west side, from E. 100th (left of No.1) to 101st (right of No. 2) Streets, showing units of Mt. Sinai Hospital as viewed southward from 101st Street and a cross a clearance at the S.E. corner of same. The low building is the Dispensary and the other, the Training School for Nurses. Upon the clearance seen in the foreground stood a row of structures that bore No's. 1455 to 1465. These were reported for demolition in the N.Y. Times of April 26, 1938. Thru their sites ran the old Eastern Post Road, in a line with the photographers point of view in No. 1.

September 14, 1938.
Views 1 and 2

P.L. Sperr
